Head through lobby past elevators through lounge area and up stairs. Immediately to your left against the wall, before curtain leading to bar. Wheelchair lift is here too.  No ramp though.

Alternatively, head through lobby to elevators, you'll see stairs going down (with restrooms painted on the wall). Follow signs to bathrooms. There are two large washrooms with stalls but signing is gender neutral.
comment: They run a lot of events in evenings in the lounge space so that may be better during the day. Downstairs will be a better option then. No hotel key required and events mean people are alerts coming and going.

UIC is a big commuter school with a lot of nontraditional students, so even if you don't look like a stereotypical college student, you're probably not going to be turned away. This restroom is very large; it's big enough to support a power chair or scooter. There are two handrails by the toilet.

Head through under the roof and take an immediate left behind the dividing fence, which obscures the entrance to the restrooms from the garden.
comment: Two gendered, single-stall locking bathrooms and a drinking fountain, and a bench nearby. Because it's in the Museum District it should be a pretty accepting area and safe place as well. name: Angelika Theater - Mockingbird Station
directions: The Angelika Theater has a bar lounge as well as an upstairs theater access. The second level has traditional gendered bathrooms with up to 12 stalls.However, the unisex accessible bathroom is on the first floor. Go into the building, head toward the bar and straight back past the staircase. The bathroom is on the left, back wall near the newspapers and magazine stands.
comment: Very clean, nice smelling bathroom with both paper towels and airdryers. Plenty of room for wheelchair and at least 2 additional people. No changing table.Movie theater level has an elevator (not readily visible - ask attendant for directions). I love the Angelika!

comment: This is unusual for a Starbucks in that there's only one restroom.

name: Cafe Brazil
directions: Bathrooms are to the left of the counter/bar, to the right of the coffee station. The bathrooms are large, lockable, and usually well-kept. Men's room has both toilet and urinal.
comment: This Cafe Brazil is pretty queer-friendly and located near SMU so it is usually well populated by college kids. The coffee is great, parking is terrible!

name: Cafe Brazil
directions: Straight ahead of the front entry, women\\'s is to the right and down the hall. MUST be a paying customer, they are strict about this.
comment: Small, single person, lockable toilet. Men\\'s is usually well-kept.

name: The Brick & Joe's
directions: There are several toilet locations. The first bathrooms are in the main room, at the back beyond the dancefloor/stage. These ARE gendered bathrooms. The men's room has three urinals and ONE toilet in a stall that locks. I haven't seen the women's.In the second half of the club, there are three gender-free single-stall locking toilets behind the pool table. They have always been clean/well kept when I've been.
comment: The Brick is a gay club geared toward men who like men (especially half naked boys) but very open to all genders. You'll see all kinds here, lots of women, transwomen, drag queens, and a few transmen.Go to:http://www.brickdallas.com/For info on hours, age restrictions, and cover charges.

name: Canterbury House Chapel and Student Center
directions: There are two bathrooms here with no gender markers. They are large, accessible rooms with a single toilet and sink, and extremely well kept. The first is on your immediate right when you first walk in the front door. The second is around the corner, two rights, near doors that lead to the stairway, lounge, and chapel proper.
comment: A+! :) This is a student center and chapel mainly for Episcopal students of SMU. However, it is open to ALL people. The ministry is (currently) VERY inclusive, LGBTQ+ friendly and knowledgeable.It is only open certain hours, and you might run into the chaplain or students who will want to speak to you, but for the most part anyone there will be friendly and helpful, and okay if all you want to do is pee and get out.More info at:http://www.canterburydallas.org/

comment:
Sundays from 10am-12pm
Office is also open from 9am-3pm Tuesday through Thursday. However, for employee safety, we don't allow anyone unknown in the building unless two or more employees/members are present. Call ahead at 214-823-2117. Also let us know if you need a shower and/or toiletries and snack items.

Staff is extremely accommodating and are all queer in some way themselves. If you are a homeless queer youth, I know it's a safe place to stay up until about 8:00 at night out of the heat, with friendly youth and staff. Staff can provide you with many programs to help with finding housing.

name: Carowinds
directions:
A map of the Carowinds Park is available a little inside the entrance, and marks all restrooms, including family restrooms. 

They are typical family restrooms scattered about the park, including (but not limited to) four in Camp Snoopy, and two in Carousel Park. 

The ones in Camp Snoopy are located near Harmony Hall and Charlie Brown Wind Up.

 The ones in Carousel Park are located near one side of The Vortex and are accessible by both a regular footpath and through a side tunnel in the plant tunnel that connects Celebration Plaza to Carousel Park.

comment: If you can't find them, there is always someone at the info desk in the rotunda who can help you. Building hours are 7AM-1AM M-F, 9AM-1AM Sat/Sun during the regular fall and spring semesters. Hours are reduced during holidays and the summer semester.

name: McEniry 122A
directions:
On the first floor.
From the left side of the building: walk past lecture halls 124 and 123. On your left, immediately after the exit, you will see 122A. If you get to lecture halls 117 or 118, you've gone too far.
From the right side of the building: walk past lecture halls 117 and 118. On the right, you will see 117, 122, then 122A. If you reach the exit or rooms 124 or 123, you've gone too far.

name: College of Health and Human Services Room 110
directions: On the first floor. From any of the main entrances (those facing the courtyard with benches and the Cato College of Education): turn left onto the first hallway and walk north (in the direction of the Popp-Martin Student Union). You will eventually pass a wood-paneled staircase and elevators on the right, then rooms 103 and 109 on your left. Turn right down the hallway after room 109, and room 110 will be the first room on your right. If you reach rooms 116, 117, or 120, you've gone too far. There are also building maps on the walls in several locations incase you get lost.

name: Woodward Hall Room 245B
directions:
From the main entrance on the first floor (facing athletic fields): head left until you reach room 140, and go up the stairs to the second floor. Exit the stairwell, go through the doors on your right, turn right down the hallway, and turn right again to continue down the hallway. 245B will be just ahead on your right. If you reach rooms 250+, you've gone too far.
From the main entrance on the second floor (facing the eagle statue and the College of Health and Human Services): make the first right and continue down the hallway. Take a left, then take the first right to continue down the hallway. Continue straight for a bit (you will pass a building exit on your right), then turn right again to continue down the hallway. 245B will be just ahead on your right. If you reach rooms 250+, you've gone too far.

name: 4600 E County Line Rd, Indianapolis, IN 46237, USA

name: Costco Wholesale

Using the gendered restroom should not pose any physical risk, but I can’t promise there wouldn’t be comments. I know that trans members at the other two Costcos in Indianapolis use the gendered restrooms as they please with no reported incidents.

name: First Mennonite Church

comment: Church is part of the Supportive Communities Network: http://www.bmclgbt.org/#!currentscn/ceqb

name: Trader's Joe's
directions: 3 unisex back of store

name: Trader Joes Store
directions: Family restroom at back of store. Nice and clean. Single stall, locking. Definitely ADA compliant.

name: LifeJourney Church
directions: The genderfree bathroom is a little bit hidden -- in the front of the church there are two traditional-gendered bathrooms, but if you walk past those, turn left (away from the social hall/sanctuary), walk down the hall past the offices/classrooms, and turn right at the last hallway before the exit, you will find a single-stall, gender-neutral bathroom at the end of that hall on your right.
comment: LifeJourney Church is a GLBTQ-affirming church. INTRAA and IndyBoyz/IndyGirlz hold meetings there.

name: All Souls Unitarian Universalist Church
directions: church has several gender-neutral bathrooms in various locations throughout the church, in addition to the two traditional-gendered bathrooms. some of them are often locked, but the one directly in front of the southeast entrance (on the left side of the building if coming in from the parking lot) is the easiest and most accessible. it has a stall with a door that locks, urinal and sink are outside the stall.

name: Conseco Fieldhouse
directions: Family/Unisex restrooms are on each seating level (near sections 3, 103, and 203) and near the corners of the building on the Founders level.
comment: Bathrooms are roomy and single toilet. Accessibility is great--there is plenty of room to maneuver me, my power wheelchair and my attendant. Bonus: there's almost always no waiting!

name: Locals Only Art and Music Pub

comment: Great pub with a wide beer selection, indie bands on weekends, open mike or blues jam, poetry night, experimental, electronica, jazz and improv night. See their web site at www.localsonlyindy.com.

name: Family Horizons Credit Union

comment: Open M-F 8:30-5:30 and Sat 9-noon

name: Methodist Hospital

Bathroom is to the right as you exit.Locked single stall gendered bathrooms are available up the East Elevators on floors 3-6.

name: Monon Coffee
directions: Back of the coffee house.
comment: You should probably buy something, but no one would really pay attention if you used the bathroom and left.  You can even leave out the back door.

comment: Building Hours:Mon-Fri: 7:00 am - 10:00 pmSat-Sun: 7:00 am - 7:00 pm

name: Yoya Self Service Frozen Yogurt and Bubble Tea

comment: I'm not sure if it is entirely ADA-accessible, although I remember it being large. I think there are two and both are genderfree, single-stall locking bathrooms. The staff was friendly on the day I visited, and if you like frozen yogurt, theirs is good.

directions: Circle Centre -- the restroom is on the second floor, which is accessible by elevator. It\\'s in the back near women\\'s dresses. Not sure if the store has other bathrooms.

I am not an expert on disability accessibility, but the toilet was low, there was room to manuever the space, and I think there were safety bars nearby.The store generally keeps mall hours but occasionally is open earlier or later. Normal hours are 10-9 M-Sat, 12-6 Sun.

comment: Weekdays 6am -> 6pmWeekends 10am -> 5pmAwesome coffee!

name: Unicorn Crepes
directions: By the ordering counter. Solitary unisex bathroom which requires a key, designated customers-only.
comment: Not only is it gender-neutral, it is one of the most fabulous bathrooms in Seattle. Words really can't describe it. I'm not sure it's entirely accessible, however. Although it is customers-only, it's well worth it to stop by and try these fabulous Japanese crepes... and get a free milk tea from an automated machine.

name: The Vera Project
directions: West end of the Seattle Center.
comment: theveraproject.org has classes, hours, and shows you can check out!

name: Climate Pledge Arena
directions: All-Gender and family restrooms are available near most sets of Men's and Women's Restrooms throughout the arena on every level.
comment: This is the arena in Seattle where the Kraken hockey team plays.

name: Washington Stae Ferries
directions: In the passenger deck on one side and in the center and often close to one of the staircases leading to the parked cars below
comment: The washington state ferries have a family bathroom that is gender neutral and is for a single person (or one with kids) and lockable. I have used one while going from Seattle to Bremerton enroute to Port Angeles all dressed up

name: Empire Espresso
directions: In the back

name: Roy St. Coffee & Tea
directions: In the back of the cafe, to the left of the cash register and down the hallway
comment: I walked in without buying anything, so I assume it is open to the public

name: The Dish
directions: In the back, just to the right after going in the door
comment: Small diner. Can get cramped during lunch rush

name: Oasis bubble tea
comment: Key needed

name: columbia city church of hope
directions: Right inside front door to left. There is a steepish portion to path outside door but should still be wheelchair accessible.
comment: Open and affirming congregation. Rainbow flag.

name: Potbelly Sandwich Shop
comment: Open to public, no key or access code needed

name: Kaladi Brothers Coffee
directions: Upper floor, directly in the back behind the cafe area, to the left of the stairs.
comment: Single occupancy gender-neutral bathrooms, you will need a key from the counter to get in, and may or may not need to purchase something to use them. If someone's in the bathroom already you can just wait until they come out and get the key from them. Full of trans-positive graffiti (this is important obviously.)

name: Optimism Brewing Company
comment: Don't have to purchase anything to use the restroom but it would be nice.

name: QFC
directions: Next to the beverage coolers by the self-checkout stands & down a little hall.
comment: Not the nicest bathrooms but they are single-stalled & you don't have to pay or have a code or anything.

name: Starbucks
comment: Two gender neutral restrooms. Both single stall.

name: Banh Mi Unwrapped
directions: Two single-stall restooms in the back of the restaurant

name: Safeco Field
directions: Between section 333 and 335

name: Homegrown Fremont
directions: Two gender neutral stalls on the right hand side.
comment: Technically you have to be a customer but half the time if you ask for the code the employees will give it to you out of habit, last known code was 6379.

name: Third Place Books/Vios Cafe
directions: Bathrooms are in Vios cafe, to the left side of the restaurant in the back near stairs to third place pub. Two private rooms.
comment: Just act like you're browsing for a bit - bathrooms are for Vios restaurant as well as Third Place Books.

name: Honor Coffee
street: 131 Broadway E Seattle, WA  98102 United States
directions: Back of shop on right.
comment: You have to be a paying customer.

name: Elliott Bay Book Company
directions: Go into the bookstore, take a right, walk towards the back and take another right into the internal coffee shop. Towards the back of the coffee shop on the right are two gender neutral bathroom doors. They need a key which is hanging on the counter but since it's frequently busy you'll generally just have to wait in line outside the bathroom for the key.
comment: Technically you need to be a paying customer but no one will stop you from grabbing a key or waiting in line.

name: MOHAI
directions: Up the stairs or elevator to the second floor; it should have a sign that says Restroom
comment: Have to pay to visit museum

name: Rian
comment: Act like your waiting for an order, then ask the barista for the restroom code. You can go out the back door in order to avoid awkward eye contact when you leave.

name: Woodland Park Zoo
directions: At the Penguin/West Gate begins the gift store.

name: Starbucks
directions: Straight to the back on the left of interior, you can't miss it.
comment: You do NOT have to buy anything - just ask a barista for the access code.

name: Ballard PCC Market
directions: In the back through the refrigerated section (clearly marked as a restroom)
comment: It's not specified that you have to be a paying customer, but it might be best to buy something small or pretend to browse for a few minutes. There is also a security guard by the door, but they are there to stop shoplifters, so they won't bug you.

name: Starbucks Chehalis
directions: On I-5 about half-way between Seattle, WA and Portland, OR. From either south-bound or north-bound, take exit 79 (Chamber Way). Starbucks is in front of a strip-mall, south of the big Wal-Mart and behind a Wendy's.
comment: 2 locking single gender-free bathrooms, both wheel-chair accessible. No key needed to get in (you don't have to ask for a key or anything).

name: Cold Stone Creamery
directions: To the left of the cashier's.

name: Arbor bar and restaurant
directions: One of our lgbtq friendly bars!
comment: Music is great. My son says it's like being in Seattle.

name: Salt Lake City International Airport
street: 776 N Terminal Dr, Salt Lake City, UT 84122
directions: Right at the intersection of concourse D and E, just after the security area, behind the Manchu Wok and Seattle's Best Coffee and inbetween the men's and women's bathrooms

name: Wild Rose Bar
directions: first floor, in the back
comment: one genderblind, single stall, locking door bathroom and one 3 stall women's only bathroom

name: WannaBee's Cafe
directions: Two bathrooms in back, on either side of main counter; neither is gender-specific.
comment: Locally-owned small business, a tiny cafe that sells used books and original art as well as coffee, chai, and pastries.

name: Da Vinci Cafe & Bakery
directions: In back of cafe; single-seating restroom, locking door.
comment: Da Vinci's is a gluten-free cafe, with a ridiculously huge and delicious selection of baked goods (and soups!), all of which are safe for those of us who are allergic to wheat and/or gluten.  Also has many items that are marked as egg, dairy, and/or soy f

name: Trabant Chai Lounge
directions: NE 45th St between Brooklyn Ave NE and University Way NE. Restrooms are towards the back of the shop.
comment: Two restrooms, both genderfree and accessible.

name: Cedars Restaurant
directions: Upper floor of building; corner of NE 50th St and Brooklyn Ave NE.
comment: One single-stall locking restroom for each gender.

name: Seven Gables Theatre
directions: On the main floor of the theatre, there is one unisex accessible restroom. (The other restrooms are on other floors and are gendered.)

name: Beth's Cafe
directions: In the middle of the building, near the game machines.

name: Monkey Grind Espresso Bar
directions: In the Guinevere Apartments building (but has its own entrance). One genderfree restroom in back.

name: Cafe Septieme
directions: Back end of building. Restrooms are gendered, but are individual rooms (single-stall) and locking.

name: UW Health Sciences Library
directions: T-334 Health Sciences Complex; floor 3. Main floor of the library. From the front door, go to the back and right. One genderfree accessible restroom.

name: Columbia City Ale House
directions: In the hallway just to the right of the short staircase which leads to the upper seating area.

name: Tutta Bella Neapolitan Pizzera
directions: In the hallway straight through to the back as you enter. Additional restroom upstairs.
comment: The two restrooms on the main floor are genderfree and accessable. There is no elevator, so the upstairs restroom, although genderfree, is not accessable.

name: El Diablo Coffee Co
directions: Through the seating area on the main floor out the door to the outside in back, then around to the left.
comment: These may be accessable, but if so, it's not obvious how to get there.

name: Liberty Sushi
comment: 2 ungendered restrooms

name: Victrola Coffee & Art
directions: gen-neutral restrroms also @ Victrolas at 310 E Pike St & 4132 BeaconAveSouth

name: The Space Needle
directions: on the O deck level
comment: labelled as a Family Restroom;it costs Money to get into the space needle

name: Science Fiction Museum
directions: 1 each on 1st floor and 2nd floor

name: Center for LGBT Health/Kaladi Bros. coffee
directions: Queerly gendered restroom. Two single stall locking restrooms labeled Kenneth and Barb, both drag queen barbie dolls. It is safe to use either restroom

name: Juliano's
directions: All the way in the back of the resturaunt.
comment: This place has the advantage of weird hours (open to 1:30 am or 3:00 am depending on the day), but due to it's size it's impossible to slip in and out unnoticed just to use the bathroom... Not that you'd want to though, once you smelled the pizza.

name: Lifelong AIDS Alliance
directions: The first door immediately down the hall at the Seneca Building, just past the front desk, ground floor.Mapquest will lose you; come up to it from Madison and the large signs will be more of a clue.  It is the less obvious of the two Lifelong buildings on either side of the Copy Mart.
comment: There are two buildings at Lifelong and while both have bathrooms, I'm only certain of the one in the Seneca building.  The building, which is the main client-focused building, is open from 8:30 to 5:00 every day.  The staff and volunteers are all friendly and will never judge you; the volunteers are expected not to talk about anyone they work with or for.

name: Caffeine Cafe
directions: Straight to the back and hang a left, two gender neutral, single occupancy bathrooms await!
comment: We're Trans owned and host a couple Trans events.

name: Madison Park Deli
directions: In the back of the room on the right. There are two single-stall/locking rooms with blackboard like doors. Sometimes an M and/or W will be written on them, but usually not.

name: Blue Bistro
directions: between American Apparel and Subway
comment: 12pm-130am

name: Caffe Ladro, Capitol Hill
comment: Every day, 5:30 AM to 10 PM

name: Solid Ground VR Office
directions: On first floor of four story brick building on 12th and E Jefferson st.

name: Local Color
directions: On the main road in Pike Place market, cross street Pine.
comment: Coffee shop with art for sale.www.localcolorseattle.comFree wifi.

name: Restaurant Zoe
directions: Toward the back, beside the bar.
comment: Two gendered single-toilet bathrooms. See their website for menus and prices.

name: Hopvine Pub
directions: Head to the back, past the bar and booths to the rear tables, and turn right.
comment: Two gendered single-stall bathrooms. But you should go for the happy hour (5-7) and the artichoke dip. Staff is friendly, good beer on tap.

name: Caffe Vita
directions: On the first floor. Past the order counter in the back (you can see the 'man|woman' sign from the front door).
comment: Single unisex bathroom, no key required.

name: Cloud City Coffee
street: Corner of NE 88th St. & Roosevelt Way NE
comment: 6am-7pm summer, 6am-6pm winter, free wifi, great pastriesm, breakfast and lunch items, LGBTQ friendly

name: Java Love Cafe/Baja Bistro
directions: off of hallway connecting bistro and cafe
comment: The cafe owners and staff are queer- and trans-friendly. The customers? Hard to predict.

name: Atmospheric Sciences Building
directions: Use the sidewalk-level entrance in the southwest corner of the building. Walk straight past the elevator and turn right; it will be in the corner to your right.
comment: Locking, genderfree bathroom with urinal and stall. Stall might be kind of small for a wheelchair. Building is open 8AM-5PM on weekdays only.

name: Cal Anderson Park
directions: Just north of the playfields.  It's a public restroom- no need to bother the shop owners in the neighborhood!
comment: Great tacos across the street.

name: Panama Hotel cafe
directions: one non-gendered bathroom downstairs, single occupancy, locking, not accessible

name: Bauhaus
directions: Back behind the kitchen area
comment: bauhaus has two single stall locking bathrooms, one that has an M and one that has a W but it is very strongly the culture of the regulars to use whatever bathroom is first available/treat them as gender neutral bathrooms, regardless of whatever bathroom people typically use or where they sit on the genderqueer spectrum.just walk right in. you don't have to buy anything. bauhaus employees are some of the nicest people on earth. i go there every day and have only seen them get upset at a customer ONCE, and that's because he was harassing me. i love the bauhaus

name: Victrola Coffee
directions: in the back, pick up keys from counter
comment: Joyously, creatively, inspirationally labeled, \"Spatula\" and \"Whisk\"Best espresso in town, n that's sayin sumpthin

name: QFC Uptown/Queen Anne
directions: This bathroom is located on the same floor as the store, above the parking garage and below the street entrance (there are elevators.) It is by the front end, just next to the floral department and close to the elevators.
comment: Mostly accessible going by the checklist but the door handle is a knob, not a lever.This bathroom is open 24 hours a day, like the store. It's a pretty busy store and during daytime hours no one would even notice you're not a customer. Less sure about nighttime hours, but I don't see why there would be a problem.There are gendered bathrooms in the back of the store.

name: Cornish College of the Arts
directions: Genderfree bathroom is located in the main building on the fifth floor, right next to the elevator.
comment: You can only enter the building if you're a student, but it's still a great resource to know if anyone is considering doing special programs at the school or becoming a full-time student.

name: Starbucks (12th and Columbia)
directions: Go around the corner to the right after you enter the building.

name: Chipotle
directions: Mon-Sun 11am-8pm
comment: Found on yelp reviews: \"There is only one unisex bathroom which was pretty clean and well stocked.\"http://www.yelp.com/biz/chipotle-seattle-3#hrid:vu4SrtoxLh85mGS7JCyqZQ

name: The Vera Project
directions: Downstairs
comment: Pic of the sign in 2012: http://24.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_m1s5viKeqy1qzxboqo1_500.png

name: Victrola Coffee Inc
directions: Located between Bellevue Ave & Minor Ave.
comment: Mon-Fri 6:30 am - 8 pmSat-Sun 7:30 am - 8 pm

name: Victrola Coffee Roasters
directions: Located between Hanford St & Horton St.
comment: Mon-Fri 6:30 am - 6 pmSat 7:30 am - 6 pmSun 8 am - 4 pm

name: FRED MEYER
directions: go to the area of the store labled as \"bathrooms\" (down a hallway) and right before you get to the gendered bathrooms on the left there is a single room, non gendered bathroom.

name: The Sureshot Cafe
comment: Ask for the key, and please buy something

name: Highline
comment: Also, vegan biscuits and gravy!

name: School of Social Work
directions: There is one on the 2nd floor

name: Party at Display and Costume
directions: On your right as you enter through the front doors
comment: Hours are:Weekdays 9-8Saturdays 9:30-6Sundays 11-5

name: Capitol Cider
directions: First floor
comment: Somewhat fancy/normy bar, genderfree single-person restroom.

name: Good Shepherd Center
directions: Three Options, One in the basement/first floor (accessible) by the South Stairwell, One on the second floor (accessible) by the South Stairwell, and one on the third floor which is stalled, gender-neutral, but there is a step to enter that bathroom, On the North end by all the therapists offices.
comment: Building is generally open from 8am to 8pm except on most holidays.

name: Black Coffee Co-op
directions: Get key at front desk.  Shared restroom with Raygun Lounge.  Multiple-person gender-neutral restroom.

name: Raygun Lounge
directions: Get key at counter. Shared restroom with Black Coffee Co-op. Multiple-person gender-neutral restroom.

name: Central Co-op
directions: Formerly known as "Madison Market".  Two gender-neutral restrooms in a small hallway past the fresh produce.

name: Redwood
directions: Bar.  Two gender-neutral single-stall restrooms.  One to the back left when you enter, one to the back right near the bar.

name: Top Pot
directions: To the right.
comment: Mostly for paying customers. But would be ok otherwise.

name: City Centre
directions: Third floor behind Palomino restaurant.
comment: Buy a cake pop or croissant from Starbucks or cookie from Mrs. Fields on the first floor by the elevators and they'll give you the code if you ask. There may be separate codes for the different gender bathrooms, so make sure they give you the right one.

name: Renaissance hotel
directions: Second floor of hotel, no room key needed. Top of escalator, turn right then left past the elevators.

name: Irwin's Bakery & Cafe
directions: Past the register & espresso machine on the right.
comment: Staff has been consistently friendly to trans & gender-variant people for the last few years and most likely will continue to be so.

name: Wayward Coffeehouse
directions: Back right corner past bar and sofa.
comment: http://www.waywardcoffee.com/

name: Cinerama
directions: On the second floor on the right side of the theater. Marked as a family restroom.
comment: Must be a paying customer. Marked as family restroom. Changing station. Single occupancy.

name: Pacific Place

comment: Marked as family restroom. You have to call a number and have security let you in. If you do not have a child with you, they may question you. Sometimes they wait outside the restroom and check if as soon as you step out.

name: Kaladi Brothers
directions: Key is at the front, bathrooms are to the right of the ordering area toward the back.
comment: Fun chalk board walls. Nice people. Great company.

name: Bar Sue
directions: Two restrooms to the left of the bar and back behind the kitchen.
comment: Not gendered, single occupancy, probably only for paying customers.

name: Pagliacci Pizza Call Center
directions: Down the stairs in the parking garage.
comment: It is only for employees who work at the call center/corporate office.

name: Kaladi Brothers Coffee
directions: To the rear of the cafe, visible from the main entrance.
comment: The bathrooms are Left and Right and are both single occupancy.  Get the keys from the front counter.

name: Supercuts Hair Salon
directions: It's straight back beyond the chairs, first door on the left.
comment: I don't know if you have to be a paying customer; I asked to use it before they knew I was picking someone up at the salon and they didn't question me.

name: Artusi
directions: In the back behind the food prep bar.

name: Serious Pie
directions: In the back of the restaurant
comment: First restroom is single room and labeled as unisex. Second restroom is labeled as wheelchair accessible, but before you can get to it, there is a small set of about 3 stairs. Unsure if ramp elsewhere in the restaurant.

name: La Quinta Inn
directions: In lobby across from elevators. Go in front door, turn right then right again.
comment:
Pretend like you belong there, since it's a hotel. Lobby open 24 hours. 

There are two single locking rooms marked "Restroom." Very clean and pretty.

name: Tea republik
directions: Far back at end of hallway
comment: Theoretically customers only, ask for door code.

name: Jus Bar
directions: Family restroom in back of cafe

name: Sod House Bakery
directions: Two unisex/gender neutral restrooms behind the register.

name: Starbucks

name: Fix Coffeehouse
directions: In the back

name: Lost Lake Cafe & Lounge
comment: Open 24/7

name: Gowen Hall

comment: Publicly accessible whenever the building is open, hours are listed on outside doors of building. Single stall, single occupancy, gender neutral signage.

name: Tea Republik
directions: Single stall single occupancy bathroom.
comment: Must be a paying customer to use, ask for door code at the counter.

name: Queen Bee
comment: Doesn't require purchase to use bathroom.

name: Cafe Yum

name: Party @ Display & Costume

name: Nexus Hotel
directions: In main lobby

name: barrio

name: Dilettante Mocha Cafe

name: Hello Robin
comment: Two neutral restrooms shared by hello robin and general store next store. Nice folks.

name: Slate Coffee Roasters

comment: Building is open later than the HUB, until 9:30pm weekdays. Bathroom is theoretically accessible, but don't know if building has elevator.

name: Skillet Diner

name: Caffe Vita Fremont

name: City Hall

comment: City Hall is open from 7 a.m. - 6 p.m., Monday through Friday.

name: Nordstrom

name: Cupcake Royale

name: Caffe Vitá
comment: For paying customers.

name: William H. Gates Hall, University of Washington School of Law

name: Best Buy

In the back. 
When you enter, if you head right, directly towards customer service, take a left and walk past the computers. You'll come up on the TV section. Stay to the right side of the store. There is a short hallway to the right and the restrooms are directly down it.
comment:
My wife works here and it is a very safe space. Even when I don't feel comfortable using the correct restroom other places, I have no problem going here just for the bathroom.
A large portion of the staff is part of the LGBTQ+ community, and a few (my wife included) are trans/NB.

The gendered restrooms do not have changing tables.

comment: It is a restaurant so you're probably better off to buy something, but I'm not sure if anyone would notice if you didn't. It generally is open until 9 or 10pm and can be busy at times. I've never tried to just use their bathroom though, but they do have good food..

name: Northeastern University (Speare Hall)
directions: Right at the Northeastern T stop along the E-line at the corner of Huntington Ave (going west) and Opera Place. There are at least between one and two Gender-Neutral single stall bathrooms in the basement. They are not well publicized, but if you are coming from the basement, take a left to ResNet room, then a second left before you get to ResLife room. It sounds complicated, but once you\\'re there, just wander a bit and you\\'ll find it.

name: Starbucks Coffee
directions: Starbucks is on the corner of Stuart and Dartmouth. Bathroom is in the back, next to the door into the shared hallway of the building.
comment: You should probably buy a coffee or something, but I've used it when I really need to pee before catching a train (the bathrooms at Back Bay are disgusting, and also gendered) without buying anything and not had a problem.

name: Starbucks Coffee
directions: In the back, there's a small hallway to the right. It's the first door on the left.
comment: It says \"no public restrooms\" on the door, but I've been allowed to use it.  Buying something and asking permission (or sneaking in when it's busy) might be a good idea.

name: Beth Isreal Medical Center- Shapiro Building
directions: There are at least two on the 2nd floor on the bridge between the Shapiro building and the neighboring building
comment: During off-hours the only open doorway in is through the Shapiro entrance on Brookline Ave- buidling maybe closed on weekends and late nights.

name: Emerson College Library
directions: 3rd floorduring the weekday, between 9-5 you can stroll right into the building without being carded

name: Sidney Borum Health Center
directions: LGBTQ friendly doctor office. you have to be buzzed in first though.
comment: LGBTQ friendly doctor office. you have to be buzzed in first though.

name: Emerson College (Piano Row Residence Hall)
directions: first floor at the end of the hallway
comment: during the day during the college operating semester you are free to stroll back there to use the bathroom, except during the night and the weekend.

name: North Station
directions: Inside North Station at the Commuter rail station, around the corner from the McDonalds/Dunkin'Donuts by the TD Garden Pro Shop.
comment: Not many people realize this bathroom is here!!!

name: Fenway Health (formerly Fenway Community Health Center)
directions: All of the restrooms are genderfree. On the ground floor, walk straight in through the glass doors, straight to the back wall, and make a right.  There are two separate gender-neutral single locking bathrooms, each with a sink.They seem wheelchair accessible due to their size and presence of grab-bars, but I'm not certain whether they meet all ADA requirements.Each floor has more bathrooms in the same configuration.
comment: Open Mon-Thu 8am-8pm ,and Fri 8am-7pm.

name: New England Aquarium
directions: The bathrooms on the 2nd floor, next to the cafe, are single-person locking.
comment: They are marked as \\\"family\\\" bathrooms, but individuals without kids use them all the time.   As far as getting to them - you can actually go to the cafe (and therefore the bathrooms) without paying.  Unless you are in a wheelchair - it is only elevator accessible from inside the Aquarium exhibit halls.

name: Starbucks Coffee City Hall
directions: Back and to the left
comment: You'll probably need to ask for a key, but you don't have to buy a thing.

name: Uno's

name: Chipotle

comment: Open til 10PM daily except holidays.

name: Microsoft Store in Prudential Center
directions: In the Prudential Center, the Microsoft Store is a bit past the center of the mall. The single stall gender neutral restrooms locaton are in the back left corner when facing the store. Go down the hallway in the back left corner that has a big Exit sign above it and they'll be on the right

name: Microsoft Store in the Prudential Center
directions: If facing the store go to the back through the big space that has a fair amount of tables and stools. The restrooms are to the left of that/in the back left corner. You'll see a lit up green Exit sign above the hallway that leads to the restrooms. There are two single stall restrooms at the end of that hallway on the right.
comment:
Most employees are cool with anyone walking in and using them. You may see events back in the big space and it may get more complicated to get to them during those events, but most employees are fine with you quickly moving through to get to them. 

A note while these are single stall with gender neutral signage I can't promise you won't get weird looks from other employees in the store. Most of them are cool about queer stuff, but there are certain co-workers of mine that have said some comments I have had to call out.

name: Jaho Coffee Roaster and wine bar

comment: They're nice.  Idk if you are expected to  buy anything but there's no key or code to access them.

comment: They are pretty good about letting non-customers use their bathroom, but please consider supporting your local independent bookstore! :)

name: Emmanuel Church
directions: To the right of the sanctuary, near the kitchen. No need to go down the stairs. (If coming from the street, use the door to the church nearest to Arlington St to enter the building.) There is a gender neutral bathroom sign on the wall. The bathroom itself has an unmarked wooden door with a lock sign on the outside that will read "engaged" if someone is inside.
comment: Easy access to this restroom on Sunday mornings, and often Saturday mornings if there is an open rehearsal. Other times, the door to the church may be locked, depending on the church's schedule. Friendly progressive church community-- they encourage members to put their pronouns on their name tag to make transgender members feel more welcome.

You can just grab the key, its attached to a snow scraper. Its sometimes high up, so you might have to ask the employee by the counter to grab it for you. Neither of us will give you any trouble.
comment: I'm non-binary (they/them), and I currently work here. If I'm working yay, if not, my coworker or anyone else won't have an issue with you grabbing the key. The restroom is on the left side of the building, behind the dumpster. Put the key in the top lock, and turn it to the right to unlock it. After, turn it to the left to lock it again, and drop the key off!

name: Vanderbilt University Peabody Library
directions: Peabody library faces Wyatt Lawn, the large lawn on Vanderbilt's Peabody campus. Facing the lawn from the streetside, Peabody Library is the first building on the right side of the lawn. Head up the staircase to the right of the main entrance. The restroom is on the second floor, hidden away in an alcove. It is a small single-stall, gender-neutral restroom. Room number 310B.
comment: Should be publicly accessibly during business hours. Students have card access until midnight.

name: Vanderbilt University Sarratt Student Center
directions: Via the central elevator / staircase, head up to the third floor (not 3*, but 3). From that floor, head straight down the hallway that is directly in front of the elevator, past the Multicultural Lounge and the IICC office. There are two single-stall, gender-neutral signage in the back by the water fountains. Both restrooms have automatic doors and are up to code.
comment: Sarratt student center has lots of conferences and visitors, so a stranger's entering the building won't be out of place. The front desk staff on the first floor are nice and might be willing to help with navigation. During the school year, most Vanderbilt students would also be willing to help, although not every student might know about the restrooms.

name: Vanderbilt University Cohen Hall
directions: On the bottom floor, there are two gender-neutral single-stall restrooms. One is immediately to the left of the door to the parking lot; the other is hidden among the professor offices.

name: Vanderbilt University Commons Center
directions: Second floor of the Commons Center. Directly above the dining hall, there is a large multipurpose room in front of the staircase. Looking at the doors of the multipurpose room, the gender-neutral restroom is to the right. Single-stall, gender-neutral signage, with an automatic door.
comment: The Commons Center is always open during standard business hours, and sometimes beyond those. The hall is a common place for non-student visitors to the university.

name: Margaret Cuninggim Women's Center
directions: Small building located next to the street, hidden behind a larger residential dorm. One restroom on the first floor, one on the second. Staff are kind and welcoming.

name: Vanderbilt University Student Life Center
directions: Four different restrooms on the first floor. Their room numbers are: 133, 144, 139F, and 139G.
comment: Don't recall if there is a changing table.

name: Vanderbilt University Jesup Hall
directions: Jesup hall is the half of the building that faces the large lawn. Six single-stall restrooms with gender-neutral singage, two on each floor. Room numbers: 100LA, 100LB, 200LA, 200LB, 300LA, 300LB.
comment: University directory says that the restrooms are accessible. I have not checked myself.

name: Vanderbilt University Hank Ingram House
directions: Hank Ingram hall faces the statue of Martha Rivers Ingram, opposite Memorial Hall. Only accessible to Vanderbilt students and people accompanied by Vanderbilt students. Restrooms are located in the basement, next to the commons area. Both restrooms are single-stall and have gender-neutral signage. University says that both restrooms are accessible, but the doors are not automatic (afaik, at least). Room numbers 112 and 114.
comment: 24/7 student card access. Accessible via elevator. Both restrooms have condom machines. No machines with menstrual products.

name: Vanderbilt University Gillette Hall
directions: Gillette Hall is right next to the road, with a small traffic circle in front of it. Facing the front of the Commons Center, Gillette Hall is to the left. The restrooms are on the ground floor (floor 1). Head to the common area at the back of the floor. The music rooms will be on your right. Walking towards the music rooms, the restrooms will be in a hallway to the right of the music rooms. Both restrooms are single-stall and have gender-neutral signage. University documentation says that they are accessible, but (afaik) neither door is automatic. Building is accessible only to Vanderbilt students.
comment: 24/7 student access (I think).

name: Vanderbilt University Garland Hall
directions: Garland Hall is located on library lawn. Facing the statue of Judge Vanderbilt, Garland Hall is at the top of the lawn, on the right. Entering the Hall through this door, head to the basement (one floor down). The two restrooms are in the center of the hallway, located on the left. Both restrooms are single-stall and have gender-neutral signage. Are handicap accessible, but I don't recall if their doors are automatic. (The building does have an elevator, but I'm not sure where.) Room numbers 006 and 008.
comment: Should be publicly accessible during business hours. 24/7 access for Vanderbilt students. The building receives a decent number of visitors, so a stranger entering the building won't go noticed.

name: Vanderbilt University Calhoun Hall
directions: The building has two staircases. Both staircases lead to the basement, but only the LEFT staircase leads to the gender-neutral restrooms in the basement. Both restrooms are single-stall and have gender-neutral signage; they're both also supposedly accessible, but their doors are not automatic.  I don't think there's an elevator that leads down from the main floor, but the basement is also accessible from a door on the left side of the building. Located near the vending machines in the basement. Room numbers 000LA and 000LB.
comment: Hall is open during business hours. The basement is ill-frequented, so there won't really be anyone around. 24/7 access for Vanderbilt students. (Also, remember to take the LEFT staircase.)

name: Vanderbilt University Alumni Hall
directions: Alumni Hall faces directly onto Vanderbilt's Alumni Lawn, and is located across the sidewalk from the Vanderbilt Barnard construction. Entering the building will leave you on the first floor, which is where the restrooms are located. Both restrooms are located in a hallway leading away from the main dining area / entrance. If you can't find a restroom, try the other hallway. Restrooms are single-stall and have gender-neutral signage. They are also marked as accessible, although they do not have automatic doors. Room numbers 104 and 105.
comment: The building is mostly only accessible via stairs. Open during standard business hours.

name: Vanderbilt University McGill Hall
directions: Upon entering through the main lobby, head to the right and go down the staircase to find the single-stall, gender-neutral restroom in the basement. Head up the staircase one floor and take a left to find the multi-stall, gender-neutral restroom on the third floor. If entering through the TV Lounge, travel through the lounge and then leave through the lounge's door. The single-stall restroom will be immediately to the right, and the central staircase is directly ahead. Heading up the central staircase to the third floor / "crying Jesus floor" and taking a left will lead to the multi-stall gender-neutral restroom. Both restrooms are supposedly accessible; neither has an automatic door.
comment: McGill Hall is a residential dorm at Vanderbilt and only students who live in the dorm have access. Most students in the hall are nice, though, and will open the door for strangers, if that person really needs to use the restroom. Please use respectfully. (Also, the central staircase has lots of paintings, some of which might be a little scary. Content warning.)

If you overlook it, ask the person at the lobby's desk. I am unsure if the men's room on the ground floor is a single stall, and I haven't been to it yet, so I don't know. 

The door is too narrow to fit most wheelchairs and the bathroom is small. The building is very old and that part of it hasn't been updated for accessibility.

name: Community College of Baltimore County Essex
directions:
There are several.
Library: straight through the entrance, turn left in the lobby, first door on your right.
Mathematics and Science Hall (MASH): there are eight of these restrooms in the building and every one is located in the central hallway across from the elevator on every floor.
comment: You technically have to be a student to use them and we do have campus security, but if you're college age and you look like you belong there, they probably won't bother you. There is a considerable amount of walking involved to get to each bathroom, so if you have mobility issues or it's an emergency, this may not be the best option.

I forgot to look and see about whether both doors are automatic though. Both stalls are labelled with the "unisex" symbol

name: BWI Marshall Airport
directions: BWI Marshall has family restrooms in many locations throughout the terminal building. There are four on Concourse A - one before security between security and the bank, one just past security near the Phillips restaurant, one at gate A9 and one in baggage claim on the lower level.There are five family restrooms in the Concourse B area - one at security, one near the Silver Diner restaurant, one at gate B2, another at gate B7 and one at baggage claim belt 5.Concourse C has two family restrooms - one in the upper level back hallway near the Lost & Found office and one at gate C7.There are four near Concourse D - one is in the upper level back hallway near Bill Bateman's restaurant, one in the back hallway behind the Air Tran Airways ticket counter, another at gate D7 and one at baggage claim belt 12.
comment: i've only used the family bathroom near the M&T Bank, a janitor unlocked the door for me. the door closed automatically (it took a few seconds) and has a manual lock on it. I think the family bathrooms are usually open/available for use but I'm not sure. I don't know which ones are accessible.

The coffee is good and strong, served in many different ways (pour-over, airpot, french press) the tea is wonderful; they just created their own \"Letterbox\" brand and the food is delicious. Many people come in just to look around, but if you have the time and money, all of their products are made locally, in-house, and very delicious. I would suggest getting pour over coffee instead of drip, it is a few cents more, but you won't regret it!

As you walk in, directly behind reception is a short hall with two restrooms, one on each side. The left is labeled "women's" and the right is "gender neutral / family / handicap". Each restroom just has one toilet and nobody cares which restroom you use. 
There is a second (but unlabeled) unisex restroom if the first one is taken: if you walk in the salon, continue walking into the salon towards the back right side of the building. Continue down the salon and walk all the way back, past the last haircutting station will be a room with shampoo bowls. There are two unlabeled doors to your left; the first door on the left is a unisex restroom with one toilet and sink.
comment: If you are just coming in to use the restroom, it's best to pretend to browse products for just a minute because I don't know if they are for paying customers or not. Tell reception you're just looking at product and then if you can't see the bathroom, just ask where it is and they'll point you in the right direction.

name: Georgia State University - Kell Hall
directions: This is on the first floor of Kell Hall, near the Peachtree Center Ave entrance, just before the elevators. ------- As of July 2011, if you enter the building from the Peachtree Center Ave entrance, there will be a large open space eventually connecting to Sparks Hall in front of you; a very large sign for and small hallway to the Cooperative Learning Lab to your right; and a short hallway leading to the elevators to your left. ------- Turn left and walk a few yards - there will be a small alcove with a women's restroom and this single-occupancy, accessible, non-gender-specific bathroom.
comment: __Locking the door:__ It may not be immediately clear, but the door to this bathroom *does* lock. It does not have a physical latch, but in the corner across from the toilet (diagonal from the sink) there are two buttons at about three feet above the floor. One locks the door and the other unlocks and automatically opens the door. ------- __Accessibility button by the door:__ This button to automatically open the door does not work. The buttons in the corner described above function fine. ------- __Hours:__ GSU is open late - especially this building, which tends to host a lot of astronomy labs. This building will probably be locked very late at night and very early in the morning, and may have somewhat more limited hours during the summer. ------- __More info about this building:__ The official university webpage for Kell Hall is at  http://www.gsu.edu/site2005/29529.html  or  tinyurl.com/gsukell . ------- __User-Safety:__ Our school is very racially diverse, so campus security is not likely to harass users of this bathroom who are not GSU students *solely* on the basis of their ethnicity, but the police at GSU and in downtown Atlanta in general have been 'cracking down on homelessness' (i.e., perpetuating racism and classism like it'll fix the economic and structural problems in the city), so you may get flack or worse if you 'look' very poor, especially if you are older than traditional college student age and not white.

comment: Open almost every day from 6 am to 2am, weekend hours vary. Be careful though, my friend (a cis-male) needed to use the restroom and the men\\'s was occupied, so he used the women\\'s marked one. A maintenance lady saw him exit and a huge ordeal occurred at the school.

directions: Two bathrooms in the front room of this coffee shop; both are gender-neutral, single room, and locking.
comment: Zotz has a pretty queer-friendly, alternative crowd. The crackberry (hibiscus blackberry) iced tea is amazing. Free wifi. Hot staff. Open 6am until 1am or so.

name: Rue de la Course
directions: Go directly through the coffee shop, past the counter, toward the back wall. On the left behind the counter and sugar/creamer area is a hallway with both bathrooms. Single stall, gendered, locking, but I see people use the opposite bathroom all the time. This place gets very busy on weekends, so it's easy to slip in and out unnoticed.
comment: Mushroom and brie soup is great, as is the coffee. The horoscopes posted on the tip jar are always freakishly accurate (for me, anyway). Grab a flyer for a local band or a free magazine on the way to the bathroom.

name: Avenue Pub
directions: The bathrooms on the first floor are gendered and have multiple stalls. BUT the bathroom on the second floor is gender-neutral and a single room, locking bathroom! Unfortunately, the bar doesn't open upstairs all the time. If you go on a trivia night or a weekend night, it will be open.
comment: Patio drinking here is pretty badass. As is the beer selection. The crowd has gotten a bit more young professional after the recent renovation, but don't let that scare you away. It's a pretty chill bar, and they've hosted queer events before.

name: Latter Library
directions: 1st floor in the back hallway thats to the right of the circ desk, just past the copy machine.
comment: Hours:9 am - 8 pm, Mon. & Wed.9 am - 6 pm, Tues. & Thurs.10 am - 5 pm, Sat.12 pm - 5 pm, Sun.Phone:504 596-2625 More info:http://neworleanspubliclibrary.org/~nopl/info/branches/branches.htm

name: Bean Gallerry

name: Community Church Unitarian Universalist

comment: In the evening, you may need to be a paying customer, but in the daytime, you can go in and just ask a few questions about the place. People who work there are progressive artists, and are tolerant and kind.

name: Toups Meatery

name: Seed

name: Seed

comment: it's a chill restaurant. I don't know for sure if you have to be a paying customer but they were all friendly and I imagine just coming in to use the restroom wouldn't be an issue. the beautifully decorated signs on the two doors say "all welcome"

name: Seed
directions: straight ahead when you come in, to the left
comment: it is a chill restaurant. i don't know for sure if you have to be a paying customer but i doubt it. they were all friendly and the beautifully painted signs on the bathroom doors say "all welcome!"

There are two, both accessible and gender neutral. There are both stairs and a ramp for accessing the coffee shop.
comment: The staff is very friendly and many of the baristas are queer and/or gender non-conforming. If you’re not purchasing anything and want to walk in unnoticed and use the restrooms, the side door is a better option, but I doubt anyone who works there would stop you from using the bathroom.
